    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-07-09T19:22:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-07-09T19:22:00-05:00" n="229"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d229">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">948.53/7–954: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 229<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in the Republic of China</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d229fn1">A note on the source text states that the telegram
                        was sent at the direction of the Under Secretary; it was drafted by
                            <persName corresp="#p_MWP1">McConaughy</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-07-09T20:22:00-04:00"
                            >July 9, 1954—8:22 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>24. Department concerned at continued Chinese detention Soviet tanker <hi
                        rend="italic">Tuapse</hi> and considers immediate release advisable.
                    Department knows of no grounds recognized by international law on which tanker
                    could be confiscated. You should take up matter urgently with Foreign Minister
                    pointing out apparent lack of legal warrant for continued detention of vessel
                    and crew, and risk of Soviet reprisals which might have far reaching
                    repercussions for other Governments as well as Chinese. You should ask to be
                    informed of approximate date of intended release of vessel and those of crew who
                    do not wish to claim political asylum.</p>
                <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_RKL1">Rankin</persName> has seen this message
                    and concurs. If in your judgment your hand would be strengthened thereby, you
                    may request Foreign Minister to deliver substance of foregoing to President <pb
                        facs="0520" n="492" xml:id="pg_492"/>
                    <persName corresp="#p_CKSG1">Chiang</persName>, prefaced by statement that
                        <persName corresp="#p_RKL1">Rankin</persName> has learned that high levels
                    this Government concerned over possible consequences further detention vessel
                    and crew.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
